  "body": "Polygon offers an [archive node snapshot].\r\nOn a machine with low specs but fast connection, a faster sync strategy than syncing from scratch would be to download this \"snapshot\" of an archive node and prune it down.\r\n\r\nThe `integration` tooling allows to change the prune flags with an \"if you know what you are doing\" warning.\r\n\r\nSo allow me to ask: in this case alone -- that is, before the first startup of a \"snapshot\" of an archive node -- is it safe to run `./build/bin/integration force_set_prune --datadir <> --prune.h.older=250000 --prune.r.older=250000  --prune.t.older=250000  --prune.c.older=250000\"`? \r\nWill it convert the archive node to a pruned node and resize the chaindata folder down from the 5TB is it now to the ~1.5TB a full node should be?\r\n\r\n[archive node snapshot]: https://wiki.polygon.technology/docs/operate/snapshot-instructions-heimdall-bor/",
